<div id="review_511750620" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/511750620" />
    <a title="Roxanne Russell" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12406850-roxanne-russell"><img alt="Roxanne Russell" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1528315296p2/12406850.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/511750620?book_show_action=true">Jan 20, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Roxanne Russell" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Roxanne Russell" href="/user/show/12406850-roxanne-russell">Roxanne Russell</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12406850-roxanne-russell?shelf=pulitzer-fiction">pulitzer-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer511750620" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2751770100049688303">I can&apos;t believe I made it to 31 with a focus on American Literature in my education, and I was never required to read this excellent story of an independent, realistic Gullah woman. Time on Cat on a Hot Tin Roof and The Sun Also Rises was wasted in comparison to the quality of simple but lyrical form and profound but individualistic revelation in this book. Peterkin captures a language and culture of this regional people as though it is her own, because partly it was. I&apos;ve wondered many times wh</span>
  <span id="freeText2751770100049688303" style="display:none">I can't believe I made it to 31 with a focus on American Literature in my education, and I was never required to read this excellent story of an independent, realistic Gullah woman. Time on Cat on a Hot Tin Roof and The Sun Also Rises was wasted in comparison to the quality of simple but lyrical form and profound but individualistic revelation in this book. Peterkin captures a language and culture of this regional people as though it is her own, because partly it was. I've wondered many times why I tend to prefer masculine fiction &amp; my admiration for this novel may have uncovered it ---&gt; I want to read more truthful, down to the bone feminine fiction.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2751770100049688303" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
